# Azure Deployment Plan for food-ordering-system

## Goal

Deploy the existing Docker-based microservices application from the current AWS/ECS-oriented setup to Azure with the smallest practical architecture change.

## Project Information

- App name: food-ordering-system
- Type: containerized microservices application with one frontend and four backend services
- Frontend: Next.js 16, React 19, TypeScript, Dockerized
- Backend services:
  - user-service: Node.js, Express, MongoDB, port 3001
  - restaurant-service: FastAPI, SQLAlchemy, SQLite by default, port 3002
  - order-service: Node.js, Express, MongoDB, port 3003
  - notification-service: FastAPI, SQLAlchemy, SQLite by default, SMTP integration, port 3004
- Local orchestration: docker-compose.yml
- Current cloud assumptions: AWS ECS Fargate task definitions under infrastructure/ecs

## Recommended Azure Architecture

Use Azure Container Apps for all five containers to stay close to the current Docker-based design.

```mermaid
graph TD
  FE[frontend<br/>Azure Container App]
  US[user-service<br/>Azure Container App]
  RS[restaurant-service<br/>Azure Container App]
  OS[order-service<br/>Azure Container App]
  NS[notification-service<br/>Azure Container App]

  ACR[Azure Container Registry]
  KV[Azure Key Vault]
  LAW[Log Analytics Workspace]
  AI[Application Insights]
  MONGO[Azure Cosmos DB for MongoDB]
  PG[Azure Database for PostgreSQL Flexible Server]

  FE --> US
  FE --> RS
  FE --> OS
  FE --> NS
  OS --> US
  OS --> RS
  OS --> NS
  RS --> US

  US --> MONGO
  OS --> MONGO
  RS --> PG
  NS --> PG

  FE --> ACR
  US --> ACR
  RS --> ACR
  OS --> ACR
  NS --> ACR

  FE -. secrets .-> KV
  US -. secrets .-> KV
  RS -. secrets .-> KV
  OS -. secrets .-> KV
  NS -. secrets .-> KV

  FE --> LAW
  US --> LAW
  RS --> LAW
  OS --> LAW
  NS --> LAW
  AI --> LAW
```

## Azure Resource Mapping

AWS to Azure mapping for this repo:

- ECS Fargate task definitions -> Azure Container Apps
- CloudWatch logs -> Log Analytics Workspace + Application Insights
- AWS Secrets Manager -> Azure Key Vault
- ECR or Docker Hub images -> Azure Container Registry
- ECS internal service discovery -> Container Apps ingress and internal service URLs

## Recommended Resources

### Shared platform

- Azure Container Apps Environment
  - Purpose: host all application containers in one environment
  - Suggested baseline: Consumption profile for assignment/demo workloads
- Azure Container Registry
  - Purpose: store all built images
  - Suggested baseline: Basic if only one team/project; Standard if frequent pulls and parallel builds are expected
- Azure Key Vault
  - Purpose: store JWT secrets, database connection strings, SMTP credentials
- Log Analytics Workspace
  - Purpose: centralized logs for all container apps
- Application Insights
  - Purpose: request monitoring and diagnostics

### Service hosting

- frontend -> Azure Container App
  - Port: 3000
  - Ingress: external
  - Build input: frontend/Dockerfile
- user-service -> Azure Container App
  - Port: 3001
  - Ingress: internal or external depending on whether the frontend calls it directly from browser
  - Build input: user-service/Dockerfile
- restaurant-service -> Azure Container App
  - Port: 3002
  - Ingress: internal or external depending on frontend access pattern
  - Build input: restaurant-service/Dockerfile
- order-service -> Azure Container App
  - Port: 3003
  - Ingress: internal or external depending on frontend access pattern
  - Build input: order-service/Dockerfile
- notification-service -> Azure Container App
  - Port: 3004
  - Ingress: internal preferred
  - Build input: notification-service/Dockerfile

### Databases

- Azure Cosmos DB for MongoDB
  - Used by: user-service and order-service
  - Reason: both Node services already use Mongoose and MONGODB_URI, so this is the lowest-friction Azure fit
- Azure Database for PostgreSQL Flexible Server
  - Used by: restaurant-service and notification-service
  - Reason: SQLite is not suitable for durable multi-container Azure deployment
  - Important: both Python services currently default to sqlite+aiosqlite and will need PostgreSQL driver support added before deployment

## Required Configuration Per Service

### frontend

- Required environment variables:
  - NEXT_PUBLIC_USER_SERVICE_URL
  - NEXT_PUBLIC_RESTAURANT_SERVICE_URL
  - NEXT_PUBLIC_ORDER_SERVICE_URL
  - NEXT_PUBLIC_NOTIFICATION_SERVICE_URL
- Note: these values are currently injected at Docker build time, not runtime. For Azure, either rebuild per environment or refactor the frontend to consume runtime configuration.

### user-service

- Required environment variables:
  - NODE_ENV
  - PORT
  - MONGODB_URI
  - JWT_SECRET
  - JWT_EXPIRES_IN
  - ALLOWED_ORIGINS

### restaurant-service

- Required environment variables:
  - PORT
  - DATABASE_URL
  - JWT_SECRET
  - USER_SERVICE_URL
- Required code/dependency change before production deployment:
  - add async PostgreSQL driver such as asyncpg to requirements.txt
  - set DATABASE_URL to a PostgreSQL connection string

### order-service

- Required environment variables:
  - NODE_ENV
  - PORT
  - MONGODB_URI
  - JWT_SECRET
  - USER_SERVICE_URL
  - RESTAURANT_SERVICE_URL
  - NOTIFICATION_SERVICE_URL
  - ALLOWED_ORIGINS

### notification-service

- Required environment variables:
  - PORT
  - DATABASE_URL
  - JWT_SECRET
  - ORDER_SERVICE_URL
  - SMTP_HOST
  - SMTP_PORT
  - SMTP_USER
  - SMTP_PASSWORD
  - FROM_EMAIL
- Required code/dependency change before production deployment:
  - add async PostgreSQL driver such as asyncpg to requirements.txt
  - set DATABASE_URL to a PostgreSQL connection string

## Main Gaps To Resolve Before Azure Deployment

1. SQLite is not deployment-safe for Azure Container Apps.
   - The restaurant-service and notification-service currently use local SQLite files inside containers.
   - Container file systems are not a reliable persistence layer for this deployment model.

2. The frontend uses build-time environment variables.
   - Different Azure environments will require either separate image builds or a small runtime config refactor.

3. Secret management is still AWS-oriented in the infrastructure docs.
   - JWT secrets, Mongo connection strings, and SMTP credentials should move to Azure Key Vault or Container Apps secrets.

4. CORS must be tightened for Azure URLs.
   - ALLOWED_ORIGINS should be set explicitly to the frontend hostname.

## Deployment Strategy

### Phase 1: Provision Azure foundation

- Create a resource group
- Create Azure Container Registry
- Create Log Analytics Workspace and Application Insights
- Create Container Apps Environment
- Create Key Vault
- Create Cosmos DB for MongoDB
- Create PostgreSQL Flexible Server

### Phase 2: Prepare application configuration

- Replace AWS-specific deployment variables with Azure values
- Define secret values in Key Vault or Container Apps secrets
- Decide whether backend services are browser-facing or internal-only
- Prepare production URLs for inter-service communication

### Phase 3: Build and publish images

- Build images from each Dockerfile
- Push images to Azure Container Registry

### Phase 4: Deploy services

- Deploy internal backend services first
- Capture their internal URLs
- Deploy frontend last with the final backend URLs

### Phase 5: Validate

- Check Container Apps revisions and logs
- Hit health endpoints for all services
- Verify login, restaurant listing, order flow, and notification flow

## Practical Recommendation

For an assignment submission, the most realistic Azure target is:

- All containers on Azure Container Apps
- Cosmos DB for MongoDB for user-service and order-service
- PostgreSQL Flexible Server for restaurant-service and notification-service
- Key Vault for secrets
- ACR for images

This keeps the current microservice boundaries and Dockerfiles, and avoids a larger re-architecture.

## Suggested Next Implementation Tasks

- [ ] Add Azure Bicep files under infrastructure/azure
- [ ] Add deployment scripts for ACR push and Container Apps deploy
- [ ] Update Python services to support PostgreSQL in Azure
- [ ] Add Azure environment variable templates for all services
- [ ] Optionally refactor frontend config to runtime-based environment loading
